# Accessibility Review Checklist

Quick reference for reviewing documentation before publication.

---

## Language and readability

- [ ] Sentences are under 25 words (on average)
- [ ] Technical terms are defined on first use
- [ ] No idioms, metaphors, or figurative language that doesn't translate literally
- [ ] Common words used in place of jargon where possible
- [ ] Reading level is appropriate for the audience (Grade 8–10 for general developer docs)

## Structure

- [ ] Page has exactly one H1 (the title)
- [ ] Heading levels are not skipped (H1 → H2 → H3, never H1 → H3)
- [ ] Each heading describes the section content out of context
- [ ] Long pages (4+ sections) have a table of contents
- [ ] Lists are used for 3+ enumerable items instead of comma-separated sentences

## Links

- [ ] All link text makes sense when read in isolation
- [ ] No "click here," "read more," or bare URLs used as link text
- [ ] Links to the same destination use the same link text throughout the page

## Images and media

- [ ] Every informative image has alt text
- [ ] Alt text describes what the image shows (not just what it is)
- [ ] Decorative images have empty alt text (`alt=""`)
- [ ] Complex diagrams have a text description below or nearby
- [ ] Color is not the only way to convey information (status, errors, categories)

## Code

- [ ] All code blocks have a language specified
- [ ] Plain-language context is provided before each code block
- [ ] Comments in code label what non-obvious sections do
- [ ] Expected output or responses are labeled and shown

## Tables

- [ ] All tables have a header row
- [ ] No merged cells or nested tables
- [ ] Tables are used for genuinely tabular data, not layout

## Final check

- [ ] Heading outline (H1–H3) reads as a logical summary of the page
- [ ] All link text sounds sensible when read aloud out of context
- [ ] Page reviewed with browser reader view or screen reader (even briefly)
